================================================================================
5. POWER AUTOMATE FLOWS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5a. SRA - Get Service List
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Instant — called from Copilot Studio
Purpose: Returns service list for the service picker adaptive card
Inputs:  None
Outputs: ServiceListJson (Text)

Steps:

  1. Trigger: When Copilot Studio calls this flow

  2. List rows — sbs_Service
       Select columns: sbs_serviceid, sbs_name, sbs_description, sbs_requesttype
       Order by: sbs_name asc

  3. Select (Data Operations)
       From: List rows > value
       Map:
         value → item()?['sbs_serviceid']
                 concatenated with pipe and requesttype and pipe and name
                 Full value: concat(string(item()?['sbs_serviceid']),'|',
                             item()?['sbs_requesttype'],'|',item()?['sbs_name'])
         title → item()?['sbs_name']

       Note: Encoding id|requestType|name as the card choice value avoids a
       second flow call to resolve the service name and requestType after
       the user makes their selection.

  4. Compose
       Input: output of Select

  5. Return values to Copilot Studio
       ServiceListJson: string(outputs('Compose'))

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5b. SRA - Get Service Schema Text
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Instant — called from Copilot Studio (Quick Chat topic only)
Purpose: Returns a plain-text schema block for injection into Quick Chat
         custom instructions as a fallback if SharePoint knowledge source
         is unreliable. Optional — primary path uses SharePoint directly.
Inputs:  ServiceId (Number)
Outputs: SchemaText (Text)

Steps:

  1. Trigger: When Copilot Studio calls this flow
       Input: ServiceId (Number)

  2. List rows — sbs_ServiceField
       Filter: _sbs_serviceid_value eq @{triggerBody()?['ServiceId']}
       Expand: sbs_fieldid($select=sbs_fieldname,sbs_displayname,sbs_fieldtype,
               sbs_validvalues,sbs_section,sbs_helptext)
       Order by: sbs_displayorder asc

  3. Apply to each row — build schema text block
       Initialize variable SchemaLines (Array) before loop.
       Inside loop, append a formatted string per field:

       Field: [sbs_displayname] ([sbs_fieldname])
       Type: [sbs_fieldtype]
       Section: [sbs_section]
       Required: [sbs_isrequired]
       Valid Values: [sbs_validvalues if not null, else "Any"]
       Conditional: [if sbs_isconditional: "Only required when " + conditionalonfield + " = " + conditionalvalue, else "Always shown"]
       Help: [sbs_helptext]
       ---

  4. Join array to single string with newline separator

  5. Return values to Copilot Studio
       SchemaText: joined string

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5c. SRA - Submit Request
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Instant — called from Copilot Studio (both Quick Chat and Form)
Purpose: Parses completed payload and writes request record to Dataverse
Inputs:  ServiceId (Number), RequestType (Text), PayloadJson (Text)
Outputs: RecordId (Text)

Steps:

  1. Trigger: When Copilot Studio calls this flow
       Inputs: ServiceId (Number), RequestType (Text), PayloadJson (Text)

  2. Compose — clean payload JSON
       Input: triggerBody()?['PayloadJson']
       Note: If Quick Chat payload contains "complete": true, strip it here.
       Use replace() expression:
         replace(triggerBody()?['PayloadJson'], '"complete": true,', '')
         replace result with '"complete": true' (trailing) also removed.
       Alternatively handle in Parse JSON schema by marking complete as optional.

  3. Parse JSON
       Content: output of Compose step
       Schema: generate from a sample Just Print Me payload object.
       Minimum schema shape:
       {
         "requestType": "",
         "requestTitle": "",
         "charging": {
           "chargeCostType": "",
           "clientMatterNumber": "",
           "thirdPartyConsent": false,
           "insiderListRequested": false,
           "glCode": ""
         },
         "supply": {
           "supplyMethod": "",
           "supplyOfficeLocation": "",
           "sourceLink": ""
         },
         "printSpecifications": {
           "numberOfCopies": 0,
           "colourMode": "",
           "paperSize": "",
           "paginationRequired": false,
           "paginationInstructions": "",
           "finishingOption": "",
           "staplePosition": ""
         },
         "return": {
           "returnMethod": "",
           "returnLocationDetails": "",
           "returnDateTime": ""
         }
       }

  4. Create a new row — sbs_Request (or your target request table)
       sbs_serviceid:      ServiceId input
       sbs_requesttype:    RequestType input
       sbs_payloadjson:    cleaned PayloadJson string
       sbs_requesttitle:   body('Parse_JSON')?['requestTitle']
       sbs_status:         "Submitted"
       sbs_submittedon:    utcNow()
       sbs_submittedby:    triggerOutputs()?['headers']?['x-ms-user-name']
                           (populated if called from authenticated context)

       Map individual parsed fields to discrete columns if your request
       table has them. The sbs_payloadjson column stores the full JSON as
       an auditable fallback regardless.

  5. Return values to Copilot Studio
       RecordId: string(outputs('Create_a_new_row')?['body/sbs_requestid'])

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5d. SRA - Card Builder (Child Flow)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Instant — child flow called by SRA - Nightly Card Rebuild
Purpose: Builds adaptive card JSON for a single service from its field
         definitions. Writes result back to the sbs_Service record.
Inputs:  ServiceId (Number)
Outputs: CardJson (Text), Success (Boolean), ErrorMessage (Text)

Steps:

  1. Trigger: Manually trigger a flow (child flow trigger)
       Input: ServiceId (Number)

  2. Get row — sbs_Service
       Row ID: ServiceId input

  3. Condition — override check
       If: sbs_cardoverridejson is not null AND is not empty
         True branch:
           Set variable CardJson = sbs_cardoverridejson
           Go to step 14 (Return)
         False branch:
           Continue to step 4

  4. List rows — sbs_ServiceField
       Filter: _sbs_serviceid_value eq @{triggerBody()?['ServiceId']}
       Expand: sbs_fieldid($select=sbs_fieldname,sbs_displayname,sbs_fieldtype,
               sbs_validvalues,sbs_section,sbs_helptext)
       Order by: sbs_displayorder asc

  5. Initialize variable: CardBodyItems (Array) = []

  6. Initialize variable: CurrentSection (String) = ""

  7. Apply to each — iterate ServiceField rows

       7a. Condition — new section
             If: item()?['sbs_fieldid']?['sbs_section'] is not equal to CurrentSection
             True branch:
               Set CurrentSection = item()?['sbs_fieldid']?['sbs_section']
               Append to CardBodyItems:
               {
                 "type": "TextBlock",
                 "text": "[Section display name — see Appendix B]",
                 "weight": "Bolder",
                 "size": "Medium",
                 "spacing": "Large",
                 "separator": true
               }
               Note: Use a Switch on CurrentSection value to map to display
               name. See Appendix B for section display names.

       7b. Condition — field type routing
             Switch on item()?['sbs_fieldid']?['sbs_fieldtype']

             Case "Text":
               Build element:
               {
                 "type": "Input.Text",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname]",
                 "placeholder": "[sbs_helptext]",
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "errorMessage": "[sbs_displayname] is required"
               }

             Case "URL":
               Build element:
               {
                 "type": "Input.Text",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname]",
                 "placeholder": "[sbs_helptext]",
                 "style": "url",
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "errorMessage": "Please enter a valid URL"
               }

             Case "Number":
               Build element:
               {
                 "type": "Input.Number",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname]",
                 "placeholder": "[sbs_helptext]",
                 "min": 1,
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "errorMessage": "[sbs_displayname] is required"
               }

             Case "Boolean":
               Build element:
               {
                 "type": "Input.Toggle",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]",
                 "title": "[sbs_displayname]",
                 "label": "[sbs_helptext]",
                 "valueOn": "true",
                 "valueOff": "false",
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true]
               }

             Case "DateTime":
               Append two elements — Date first, then Time:
               {
                 "type": "Input.Date",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]_date",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname] — Date",
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "errorMessage": "Date is required"
               },
               {
                 "type": "Input.Time",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]_time",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname] — Time",
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "errorMessage": "Time is required — a date alone is not sufficient"
               }
               Note: The Submit flow must concatenate [fieldname]_date and
               [fieldname]_time into a single ISO datetime before writing
               to Dataverse.

             Case "Choice":
               Parse sbs_validvalues JSON array.
               Map each value to: { "title": "[value]", "value": "[value]" }
               Build element:
               {
                 "type": "Input.ChoiceSet",
                 "id": "[sbs_fieldname]",
                 "label": "[sbs_displayname]",
                 "placeholder": "Select...",
                 "style": "compact",
                 "isRequired": [sbs_isrequired],
                 "isVisible": [if sbs_isconditional then false else true],
                 "choices": [mapped choices array],
                 "errorMessage": "[sbs_displayname] is required"
               }

       7c. Append built element(s) to CardBodyItems

  8. Compose — full adaptive card envelope
       {
         "$schema": "http://adaptivecards.io/schemas/adaptive-card.json",
         "type": "AdaptiveCard",
         "version": "1.3",
         "body": [CardBodyItems variable],
         "actions": [
           {
             "type": "Action.Submit",
             "title": "Submit Request",
             "style": "positive"
           }
         ]
       }

  9. Set variable: CardJson = string(outputs('Compose'))

  10. Update row — sbs_Service
        Row ID: ServiceId input
        sbs_cardjson:          CardJson variable
        sbs_cardlastupdated:   utcNow()
        sbs_cardbuildstatus:   "Built"

  11. Return values
        CardJson:    CardJson variable
        Success:     true
        ErrorMessage: ""

  Error handling (configure on the scope wrapping steps 4-10):
    On failure:
      Update row — sbs_Service
        sbs_cardbuildstatus: "Failed"
      Return values:
        CardJson:     ""
        Success:      false
        ErrorMessage: error message string from failed action

  NOTE ON CONDITIONAL VISIBILITY
  Adaptive Cards 1.3 does not support native conditional show/hide based on
  another field's value within the same card. Conditional fields are rendered
  with isVisible: false by default. To enable dynamic show/hide you have two
  options:

  Option A — Multi-step cards (recommended for Copilot Studio)
    Split the form into logical sections across multiple sequential cards.
    Each card submission triggers the next card, with conditional cards
    only rendered when their parent condition has been confirmed.
    Implement this as multiple Question nodes in the Form topic rather than
    a single card render.

  Option B — Action.ToggleVisibility (Adaptive Cards 1.2+)
    Add Action.ToggleVisibility actions to Choice inputs so selecting a value
    reveals hidden fields. Requires card-level action bindings and is more
    complex to generate dynamically. Test host support in Copilot Studio
    before committing to this approach.

  The card builder generates isVisible: false on conditional fields in all
  cases. Which visibility behaviour is applied is determined by the Form
  topic implementation, not the card builder.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5e. SRA - Mark Card Pending on ServiceField Change
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Automated — Dataverse row trigger
Purpose: Marks a service card as Pending rebuild when any of its field
         mappings are created, updated, or deleted.
Trigger: When a row is added, modified, or deleted — sbs_ServiceField table

Steps:

  1. Trigger: When a row is added, modified, or deleted
       Table: sbs_ServiceField
       Scope: Organisation

  2. Get row — sbs_ServiceField
       Row ID: triggerOutputs()?['body/sbs_servicefieldid']
       Note: Needed to resolve the ServiceId lookup value.

  3. Update row — sbs_Service
       Row ID: outputs('Get_row')?['body/_sbs_serviceid_value']
       sbs_cardbuildstatus: "Pending"

  Note: This flow fires on every ServiceField change during business hours.
  The card is NOT rebuilt immediately — the status is simply flagged. The
  nightly flow handles the actual rebuild. This keeps the trigger flow fast
  and avoids rebuilding cards multiple times if several fields are updated
  in quick succession.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5f. SRA - Mark Cards Pending on Field Change
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Automated — Dataverse row trigger
Purpose: When a shared field definition changes (e.g. valid values updated),
         marks all services using that field as Pending rebuild.
Trigger: When a row is modified — sbs_Field table

Steps:

  1. Trigger: When a row is modified
       Table: sbs_Field
       Scope: Organisation

  2. List rows — sbs_ServiceField
       Filter: _sbs_fieldid_value eq @{triggerOutputs()?['body/sbs_fieldid']}
       Select columns: sbs_servicefieldid, _sbs_serviceid_value

  3. Apply to each — iterate ServiceField rows
       Update row — sbs_Service
         Row ID: item()?['_sbs_serviceid_value']
         sbs_cardbuildstatus: "Pending"

  Note: A single field change could affect many services. This flow will fire
  one Update row action per affected service. For 88 services sharing a common
  field, that is 88 updates — acceptable, but be aware of Power Automate API
  call consumption.

  Optimisation if needed: Select distinct ServiceIds first, deduplicate
  using a union or group-by step, then update only unique records.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5g. SRA - Nightly Card Rebuild
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Type:    Scheduled
Purpose: Rebuilds adaptive card JSON for all services marked as Pending.
         Runs out of hours to avoid impacting agent performance during the day.
Trigger: Recurrence — daily at 23:00 (adjust to suit your maintenance window)

Steps:

  1. Trigger: Recurrence
       Interval: 1
       Frequency: Day
       At: 23:00 local time (configure timezone explicitly)

  2. List rows — sbs_Service
       Filter: sbs_cardbuildstatus eq 'Pending'
       Select columns: sbs_serviceid, sbs_name, sbs_requesttype

  3. Condition — any pending services?
       If: length(outputs('List_rows')?['body/value']) is greater than 0
       True branch: continue to step 4
       False branch: terminate (nothing to do)

  4. Apply to each — iterate Pending service records
       Concurrency: set to 1 to avoid rate limiting on Dataverse writes.
       Increase to 5 if rebuild volume grows and rate limits allow.

       4a. Update row — sbs_Service
             Row ID: item()?['sbs_serviceid']
             sbs_cardbuildstatus: "Building"
           Note: Mark as Building before calling child flow so a second
           nightly run does not pick up the same record if the flow is slow.

       4b. Run child flow — SRA - Card Builder
             ServiceId: item()?['sbs_serviceid']

       4c. Condition — Success check
             If: outputs('Run_child_flow')?['body/Success'] is equal to true
             True branch:
               No further action needed — Card Builder already updated the
               sbs_Service record with Built status and card JSON.
             False branch:
               Update row — sbs_Service
                 sbs_cardbuildstatus: "Failed"
               Post adaptive card to Teams channel (optional monitoring):
                 Alert: "Card build failed for service [name]: [ErrorMessage]"

  5. (Optional) Send summary notification
       After Apply to each completes, compose a summary of Built vs Failed
       counts and post to a monitoring Teams channel or send via email.

================================================================================
6. COPILOT STUDIO TOPICS
================================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6a. Topic: Conversational Start (System Topic — modify existing)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Trigger: System - Conversation Start
Purpose: Service picker, mode picker, route to Quick Chat or Form.

Node 1 — Send Message
  Text: "Welcome to the Service Request Agent. Loading available services..."

Node 2 — Call Power Automate
  Flow: SRA - Get Service List
  Output: Topic.ServiceListJson (Text)

Node 3 — Ask with Adaptive Card (Service Picker)
  Card JSON:
  {
    "$schema": "http://adaptivecards.io/schemas/adaptive-card.json",
    "type": "AdaptiveCard",
    "version": "1.3",
    "body": [
      {
        "type": "TextBlock",
        "text": "What service do you need today?",
        "weight": "Bolder",
        "size": "Medium"
      },
      {
        "type": "Input.ChoiceSet",
        "id": "selectedService",
        "style": "filtered",
        "placeholder": "Search or select a service...",
        "isRequired": true,
        "choices": []
      }
    ],
    "actions": [
      { "type": "Action.Submit", "title": "Continue", "style": "positive" }
    ]
  }

  Bind the choices array to Topic.ServiceListJson at runtime.
  Each choice item has: title = service name, value = "id|requestType|name"
  Wait for response: Yes
  Output variable: Topic.ServicePickerResponse

Node 4 — Set Global Variables (parse delimited card response)
  Set Global.SelectedServiceId:
    Power Fx: Value(First(Split(Topic.ServicePickerResponse.selectedService, "|")).Value)
  
  Set Global.SelectedRequestType:
    Power Fx: Index(Split(Topic.ServicePickerResponse.selectedService, "|"), 2).Value
  
  Set Global.SelectedServiceName:
    Power Fx: Last(Split(Topic.ServicePickerResponse.selectedService, "|")).Value

Node 5 — Ask with Adaptive Card (Mode Picker)
  Card JSON:
  {
    "$schema": "http://adaptivecards.io/schemas/adaptive-card.json",
    "type": "AdaptiveCard",
    "version": "1.3",
    "body": [
      {
        "type": "TextBlock",
        "text": "How would you like to complete your request?",
        "weight": "Bolder",
        "size": "Medium"
      },
      {
        "type": "Input.ChoiceSet",
        "id": "selectedMode",
        "style": "expanded",
        "isRequired": true,
        "choices": [
          {
            "title": "Quick Chat — answer a few questions conversationally",
            "value": "QuickChat"
          },
          {
            "title": "Form — fill in a structured form",
            "value": "Form"
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "actions": [
      { "type": "Action.Submit", "title": "Continue", "style": "positive" }
    ]
  }

  Wait for response: Yes
  Output variable: Topic.ModeResponse

Node 6 — Set Variable
  Global.SelectedMode = Topic.ModeResponse.selectedMode

Node 7 — Condition
  If: Global.SelectedMode is equal to "QuickChat"
    → Node 8a
  Else:
    → Node 8b

Node 8a — Redirect to Topic: Quick Chat
Node 8b — Redirect to Topic: Form

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6b. Topic: Quick Chat
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Trigger: Called via Redirect only. No trigger phrases.
Purpose: Generative Answers loop, completion detection, Dataverse submit.

Knowledge Source (agent level):
  SharePoint library: Service Schemas
  The Generative Answers node uses this library.
  File targeting is controlled via the dynamic custom instructions.

Node 1 — Set Variable
  Topic.ConversationHistory = "" (Text, empty)

Node 2 — Set Variable
  Topic.IsComplete = false (Boolean)

Node 3 — Set Variable
  Topic.LastResponse = "" (Text, empty)

Node 4 — Send Message
  "Let's get your {Global.SelectedServiceName} request sorted.
   Tell me what you need and I'll take care of the rest."

--- LOOP START — label this node "ConversationLoop" ---

Node 5 — Question
  Question: "" (blank — question is surfaced from GA output in Node 11)
  Note: First turn uses the user's reply to Node 4's message.
  For subsequent turns the user responds to the GA question sent in Node 11.
  Entity: Free text (No entity)
  Variable: Topic.UserInput (Text)

Node 6 — Set Variable (append user turn to history)
  Topic.ConversationHistory =
    Topic.ConversationHistory & "User: " & Topic.UserInput & Char(10)

Node 7 — Generative Answers Node
  Input (context / search query): Topic.ConversationHistory

  Custom Instructions:
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------
  You are a service request assistant for the {Global.SelectedRequestType}
  service. Your knowledge source contains the schema document for this
  service. It defines every required field, field types, valid values, and
  all conditional rules.

  Review the full conversation history provided. Identify every field that
  has already been confirmed by the user. Do not ask again for a field that
  has been answered.

  Ask for missing required fields one or two at a time in a natural,
  friendly way. Apply all conditional rules — only ask for a conditional
  field when its parent condition is satisfied.

  When every required field has been collected and confirmed, respond with
  only a valid JSON object matching the payload schema in the knowledge
  document. Include all collected values and add "complete": true as a
  top-level property. Do not include any text before or after the JSON.

  Until all fields are collected, respond conversationally only. Never
  output any JSON until the request is genuinely complete.

  Never infer or assume a value. If a user provides a vague answer, ask
  for clarification before accepting it.
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Knowledge source: SharePoint — Service Schemas library
  Output variable: Topic.LastResponse (Text)

Node 7b — Condition (empty output guard)
  If: Topic.LastResponse is blank or empty
    True branch:
      Send Message: "I had trouble processing that. Could you rephrase?"
      Go to step: ConversationLoop (Node 5)
    False branch:
      Continue to Node 8

Node 8 — Set Variable (append assistant turn to history)
  Topic.ConversationHistory =
    Topic.ConversationHistory & "Assistant: " & Topic.LastResponse & Char(10)

Node 9 — Condition (completion check)
  If: Contains(Topic.LastResponse, """complete"": true")
       OR Contains(Topic.LastResponse, "\"complete\": true")
    True branch → Node 10
    False branch → Node 11

--- FALSE BRANCH: Not complete ---

Node 11 — Send Message
  Text: {Topic.LastResponse}
  (Surfaces the GA question or follow-up to the user)

Node 12 — Go to step: ConversationLoop (Node 5)

--- TRUE BRANCH: Complete ---

Node 10 — Set Variable
  Topic.PayloadJson = Topic.LastResponse
  (Raw JSON string with complete: true — the Submit flow strips the flag)

Node 13 — Call Power Automate
  Flow: SRA - Submit Request
  Inputs:
    ServiceId:    Global.SelectedServiceId
    RequestType:  Global.SelectedRequestType
    PayloadJson:  Topic.PayloadJson
  Output: Topic.RecordId (Text)

Node 14 — Send Message
  "Your {Global.SelectedServiceName} request has been submitted.
   Reference number: {Topic.RecordId}.
   The team will action this shortly."

Node 15 — End topic

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6c. Topic: Form
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Trigger: Called via Redirect only. No trigger phrases.
Purpose: Read pre-built card from sbs_Service, render, capture submission,
         write to Dataverse.

Node 1 — Send Message
  "Loading your {Global.SelectedServiceName} form..."

Node 2 — Get row — sbs_Service (via Dataverse connector action)
  Row ID: Global.SelectedServiceId
  Output variable: Topic.ServiceRecord

  Alternative: Call a lightweight PA flow that returns just the cardjson
  string if the direct Dataverse action is not available in your topic editor.

Node 3 — Set Variable
  Topic.CardJson = Topic.ServiceRecord.sbs_cardjson

Node 4 — Condition (card available check)
  If: Topic.CardJson is blank or empty
    True branch → Node 4a (fallback)
    False branch → Node 5

Node 4a — Send Message (fallback)
  "The form for {Global.SelectedServiceName} is not available yet —
   the team is setting it up. Please use Quick Chat or contact support."
  End topic.

Node 5 — Ask with Adaptive Card
  Card: Topic.CardJson (variable reference)
  
  Note: Test whether your Copilot Studio version supports rendering a card
  from a variable. If not, use a PA flow that returns the card JSON and
  immediately renders it via a Send Message with card attachment type,
  or fall back to static card JSON per service using a Switch on
  Global.SelectedRequestType.

  Wait for response: Yes
  Output variable: Topic.FormResponse

Node 6 — Set Variable
  Topic.PayloadJson = JSON(Topic.FormResponse)
  
  Note: Prepend requestType and requestTitle to the payload before
  submitting if they are not captured inside the card response.

Node 7 — Call Power Automate
  Flow: SRA - Submit Request
  Inputs:
    ServiceId:    Global.SelectedServiceId
    RequestType:  Global.SelectedRequestType
    PayloadJson:  Topic.PayloadJson
  Output: Topic.RecordId (Text)

Node 8 — Send Message
  "Your {Global.SelectedServiceName} request has been submitted.
   Reference: {Topic.RecordId}."

Node 9 — End topic

FORM TOPIC — OPEN ITEMS TO RESOLVE BEFORE BUILD
  1. Conditional field visibility: decide between multi-step card sequence
     (Option A) or Action.ToggleVisibility (Option B). See Card Builder note
     in section 5d. Resolve before card builder is built.
  2. Dynamic card JSON from variable: test this in your Copilot Studio
     version before committing to this approach. It is unreliable in some
     versions. If it fails, the fallback is described in Node 5 above.
  3. DateTime field handling: the card builder produces separate _date and
     _time input IDs. The Submit flow must concatenate these. Ensure the
     Submit flow handles this before end-to-end testing.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6d. Error Handling — Conversational Boosting Override
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Navigate to: System Topics > Conversational Boosting

Locate the fallback error message node (sends "Sorry, I wasn't able to
respond to that" or similar). Add a condition before it:

Condition:
  If: Global.SelectedMode is equal to "QuickChat"
  True branch:
    Send Message: "I had a problem with that response — let's try again."
    Redirect to: Quick Chat topic
    Note: Redirecting mid-loop will reset conversation history. This is
    acceptable as a rare fallback. The user will need to restart the
    Quick Chat flow for that service.
  False branch:
    Existing fallback behaviour (leave unchanged)

A simpler and more reliable approach is the empty output guard already
built into Quick Chat at Node 7b, which catches most Generative Answers
failures before they surface as system errors. The Conversational Boosting
override is a secondary safety net.

================================================================================
7. DEVELOPMENT ORDER
================================================================================

Build and test in this exact sequence. Each step validates the layer below
it before building on top.

  Step 1  — Create Dataverse tables from schema in Section 3
  Step 2  — Import seed data from Section 4
  Step 3  — Upload JustPrintMe.md to SharePoint Service Schemas library
  Step 4  — Build and test SRA - Get Service List (verify JSON output shape)
  Step 5  — Build Conversational Start: service picker card only
              Confirm card renders, choice selection works, global variables
              are set correctly from the delimited value
  Step 6  — Add mode picker to Conversational Start, confirm routing variables
  Step 7  — Build SRA - Submit Request with stubbed output (log inputs only)
  Step 8  — Build Quick Chat topic
              Test Generative Answers node with SharePoint knowledge source
              independently before adding the loop logic
              Then add loop, completion detection, and stub submit call
              Then connect real Submit flow
  Step 9  — Build SRA - Card Builder child flow
              Test standalone with Just Print Me service ID
              Inspect generated card JSON before wiring into any topic
  Step 10 — Build SRA - Mark Card Pending on ServiceField Change
  Step 11 — Build SRA - Mark Cards Pending on Field Change
  Step 12 — Build SRA - Nightly Card Rebuild
              Test by manually setting a service to Pending and running
              the flow on demand before setting up the schedule
  Step 13 — Build Form topic
              Test dynamic card rendering first
              Then connect Submit flow
  Step 14 — Add Conversational Boosting override
  Step 15 — End-to-end test: Quick Chat, Just Print Me, full submission
  Step 16 — End-to-end test: Form, Just Print Me, full submission
  Step 17 — Validate card rebuild cycle: modify a ServiceField row, confirm
              Pending status set, run nightly flow manually, confirm Built

================================================================================
8. APPENDIX A — FIELDTYPE TO ADAPTIVE CARD ELEMENT MAPPING
================================================================================

  FieldType   Card Element          Notes
  ---------   ------------          -----
  Text        Input.Text            style: "text"
  URL         Input.Text            style: "url"
  Number      Input.Number          min: 1 for most cases
  Boolean     Input.Toggle          valueOn: "true", valueOff: "false"
  DateTime    Input.Date +          Two separate inputs per field.
              Input.Time            IDs: [fieldname]_date, [fieldname]_time
                                    Submit flow concatenates to ISO datetime.
  Choice      Input.ChoiceSet       style: "compact" for 4+ options,
                                    style: "expanded" for 2-3 options.
                                    Choices mapped from sbs_validvalues array.

================================================================================
9. APPENDIX B — SECTION DISPLAY NAME REFERENCE
================================================================================

  sbs_section value    Display name in card
  -----------------    --------------------
  root                 Request Details
  charging             Charging
  supply               Document Supply
  printSpecifications  Print Specifications
  return               Return

  Use these mappings in the Card Builder Switch step (7a) when generating
  section header TextBlock elements.

